## 4) Exemplo prático: adicionar 1 bloco usando padrão “Botania-like” no `common`

### 4.1. `common`: define “o que existe” e expõe `register(...)`

Crie um arquivo em `common/src/main/java/.../registry/ModContent.java` (nome livre):

```java
package your.mod.common.registry;

import java.util.function.BiConsumer;
import java.util.function.Supplier;

import net.minecraft.resources.ResourceLocation;
import net.minecraft.world.item.BlockItem;
import net.minecraft.world.item.Item;
import net.minecraft.world.level.block.Block;
import net.minecraft.world.level.block.state.BlockBehaviour;

public final class ModContent {
    private ModContent() {}

    // Use path string + Supplier pra construir DURANTE o registro
    public static final String EXAMPLE_BLOCK_PATH = "example_block";

    public static void registerAll(RegistrationSink sink) {
        // 1) Registrar o bloco
        Block exampleBlock = sink.registerBlock(id(EXAMPLE_BLOCK_PATH),
                () -> new Block(BlockBehaviour.Properties.of().strength(1.5F)));

        // 2) Registrar o item do bloco (BlockItem)
        sink.registerItem(id(EXAMPLE_BLOCK_PATH),
                () -> new BlockItem(exampleBlock, new Item.Properties()));
    }

    private static ResourceLocation id(String path) {
        return ResourceLocation.fromNamespaceAndPath("seamless_sleep", path);
    }

    /**
     * “Ponte” mínima que cada loader implementa para registrar.
     * - O common só sabe: "quero registrar Block/Item com id e factory"
     * - O loader sabe: "como e quando registrar isso no meu registry"
     */
    public interface RegistrationSink {
        Block registerBlock(ResourceLocation id, Supplier<? extends Block> factory);
        Item  registerItem (ResourceLocation id, Supplier<? extends Item> factory);
    }
}
